Here is an example of automatically generating a table of contents in a LaTeX document:

\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}

Some introductory text here.

\section{Main Section 1}

Content for main section 1 here.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
Subsection content here.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
Subsection content here. 

\section{Main Section 2}

Content for main section 2 here.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
Subsection content here.

\end{document}

The key points are:

- Use the \tableofcontents command where you want the table of contents to appear.

- Use \section and \subsection commands to divide the document into sections and subsections. 

- LaTeX will automatically generate the table of contents using the section headings.

- The table of contents will contain the sections and subsections with page numbers indicating where they appear in the document.

Here is LATEX code to draw a chessboard from a FEN notation:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\chessboard[setfen=r1b1k2r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQK1NR w KQkq - 5 4]

\end{document}

The key points are:

- Include the chessboard package
- Use the \chessboard command 
- Set the fen option to the FEN notation string
- The chessboard will be drawn automatically with the pieces in the positions specified by the FEN string

The chessboard package handles all the work of parsing the FEN and drawing the board. You just need to provide the FEN string.

